<dl id="n25041b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25041b">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25041b"> 41(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> You are my villains ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25041b"><li>FW 545.13f </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n25041b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n25041b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25041b">MS BL 47484a-291</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:404 <a name="rAd8" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd8.htm#n25041b">Draft: III&sect;3B.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In several customs which divide the inheritance equally among sons, the youngest keeps the homestead, the aster or hearth. I am far from saying that the servile origin of ultimogeniture is proved, but certainly the succession of the youngest was regarded as servile in the thirteenth century. I could give you simple proof of that. It is the thus brought into connection with the merchetum. Very commonly they are mentioned together: &lsquo;<mark>You are my villains</mark>, for I have talliged you, you paid fine for your daughter&apos;s marriage, you were your father&apos;s youngest son and succeeded to his tenement.&rsquo; <small> Sir James Frazer, <a name="FLOT2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FLOT2"><cite title="source">Folk-Lore in the Old Testament</cite></a> (1923) 176</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also: <a name="n22048a" href="n22all.htm#n22048a">N22 (VI.B.17):048(a)</a> and <a name="n29152c" href="n29all.htm#n29152c">N29 (VI.B.21):152(c)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
